<p style="text-align:justify;">skipped about with great vigour and variety of Steps &#8211; now and then shrieking very loud<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>"</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">Swenburn's Travels.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Lazzaroni in Naples have no dwelling houses, but sleep every night under Porticoes, Piazzas, or any kind of shelter they can find; those among them who have wives and children live in huts or in caverns dug out of a mountain.  Do.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">As the weather is extremely warm here, and there is little need of clothing for comfort, the Lazzaroni have little care about appearances, and go with a vast deal of their persons uncovered, except by strange ornaments.  The man, who rows you about this lovely Bay, has perhaps the Angel Raphael, or the Blessed Virgin Mary delineated on one brawny sun burnt leg; and the Saint of the Town upon the other &#8211; his arms represent the glory of God, or some strange things; while brass medals hang from his neck expressive of his favourite Martyr.  Piozzi's Tr.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">In Switzerland the Roman Catholics hold a Bear's memory in great veneration, and represent him as the first convert</p>

